This paper is about dialogue response selection, which is a subfield of natural language processing (NLP) and falls under the category of Computational Linguistics (cs.CL). The paper proposes a neural network architecture that is designed to handle different sources of information, such as user utterances, system responses, and knowledge base (KB) results. This involves modeling the syntactic and semantic differences between these sources, which requires techniques from machine learning (cs.AI), deep learning (cs.LG), and information retrieval (cs.IR). Finally, the proposed model uses recurrent neural networks (RNNs) and attention mechanisms, which are commonly used in neural network architectures for NLP (cs.NE).
